1
00:00:03,693 --> 00:00:31,893
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:36,143 --> 00:00:45,073
This is one of the few times that I'm going to give a talk about which I know very little.

3
00:00:47,697 --> 00:00:55,286
So I'm hoping for lots of comments and that you'll reserve your tomatoes and eggs for the end.

4
00:00:57,628 --> 00:01:02,234
I read a very interesting essay by a man called James Kurth.

5
00:01:03,076 --> 00:01:07,120
who wrote this for the Foreign Policy Research Institute in New York.

6
00:01:08,161 --> 00:01:10,322
And he called it religion and globalization.

7
00:01:11,004 --> 00:01:23,596
But he suddenly pointed out to me the distinctions between a pre-modern, modern, and post-modern society, or should we say ethos.

8
00:01:24,656 --> 00:01:30,703
And I just began trying to think of it in terms of a Buddhist perspective.

9
00:01:30,683 --> 00:01:38,293
angle, and to try and link it, try and talk about it, just in terms of spiritual practice.

10
00:01:38,715 --> 00:01:46,066
So this isn't, I don't mean to confuse this with a comparison between different societies, that one is better than the other.

11
00:01:46,126 --> 00:01:50,111
I'm not talking about its history or its art or anything of that nature.

12
00:01:51,593 --> 00:01:54,278
All I'm doing is looking at certain

13
00:01:55,507 --> 00:02:08,090
ways in which these three societies see the process of enlightenment and see if a Buddhist, in fact, or somebody following the Buddha Dhamma, the Buddha's teaching, could actually become enlightened in any of these societies.

14
00:02:09,472 --> 00:02:12,478
That's the task.

15
00:02:12,497 --> 00:02:14,581
Get my PhD on this, huh?

16
00:02:14,602 --> 00:02:15,443
I'm in the right city.

17
00:02:15,483 --> 00:02:15,843
Thank you.

18
00:02:17,883 --> 00:02:25,957
So starting at the beginning with pre-modern society, that refers to really what we know as the medieval ages.

19
00:02:29,906 --> 00:02:39,925
And a pre-modern society depends upon revelation for its spiritual founts.

20
00:02:40,715 --> 00:03:06,132
so it's a given so in terms of both Islam and Christianity you have a given revelation which is then believed in and because of the structure of a dogma it demands that you can only have very few people

21
00:03:06,685 --> 00:03:08,206
interpreting it.

22
00:03:08,227 --> 00:03:12,453
If you have too many interpretations then you start getting what later happens, a sort of reformation.

23
00:03:13,735 --> 00:03:29,397
So you have to control the power and it fitted in well with the whole idea of Christianity at that time of establishing on earth a society, a static society which would be ready for the second coming.

24
00:03:30,879 --> 00:03:32,322
It was actually during the

25
00:03:33,247 --> 00:03:40,514
12th century thereabouts that the idea that the second coming wasn't going to happen or was going to happen in a different way began to arise.

26
00:03:43,158 --> 00:03:54,731
So what the medievalists tried to do was set up a society in which people knew exactly where they were and you had both the temporal and the spiritual and it was very hierarchical.

27
00:03:55,977 --> 00:04:01,727
So, you know, the serfs just rising up through the lords, king, and finally the emperor.

28
00:04:02,467 --> 00:04:10,822
And in the spiritual realm, the ordinary punters are down below, and then the priests, bishops, and then finally the pope.

29
00:04:14,707 --> 00:04:20,617
So it was never really a question of questioning the revelation itself.

30
00:04:21,307 --> 00:04:27,475
It was always the idea of supporting it, even when it didn't make complete sense.

31
00:04:28,757 --> 00:04:36,627
So Tertullian, who was a great theologian, said that we believe because it is absurd.

32
00:04:37,827 --> 00:04:44,497
What he meant wasn't our sense of being ridiculous, but that it was beyond rationality.

33
00:04:44,516 --> 00:04:46,740
It was something you had to believe, full stop.

34
00:04:51,057 --> 00:04:59,766
And the spiritual path was totally dependent upon a practice which took that for granted.

35
00:05:03,971 --> 00:05:13,622
So it demanded what we would call a certain faith, a certain blind faith, which gives it a sort of wrong intonation really.

36
00:05:14,901 --> 00:05:16,103
and unquestioning faith.

37
00:05:16,923 --> 00:05:25,333
That as your basis you then either practice good works or prayer and you would make sanctity.

38
00:05:26,913 --> 00:05:31,519
So I think the archetypal saint may be somebody like Saint Francis.

39
00:05:34,182 --> 00:05:43,490
Just a total belief, no questioning of the actual revelation as such, but a total giving of oneself to the practice.

40
00:05:44,904 --> 00:05:50,411
And even today you might say that somebody like Mother Therese of Calcutta fits into that sort of mold.

41
00:05:52,553 --> 00:06:02,204
When you hear her talk, there's no question that the revelation might not be true or anything of that nature.

42
00:06:07,810 --> 00:06:13,156
So what does that produce in terms of a teacher-student relationship?

43
00:06:13,930 --> 00:06:16,012
So it's one of hierarchy, isn't it?

44
00:06:16,312 --> 00:06:20,656
The teacher is in authority as well as being an authority.

45
00:06:20,995 --> 00:06:27,942
He has in authority over and the student is one who listens and follows the teacher.

46
00:06:28,101 --> 00:06:29,324
There's no question about it.

47
00:06:31,004 --> 00:06:32,987
You don't question the teacher, the teacher knows.

48
00:06:33,127 --> 00:06:34,528
It's that sort of relationship.

49
00:06:37,430 --> 00:06:42,435
And there are character types in Buddhism.

50
00:06:43,427 --> 00:07:11,814
based upon the three basic roots of greed, hatred and delusion greedy types, hateful types and deluded types and the opposite of that and this is later commentary this isn't so much in the original scriptures is the person of faith the person of intelligence and that we'll come to in a minute and the speculative type

51
00:07:12,992 --> 00:07:16,858
And they're positive, right?

52
00:07:16,877 --> 00:07:27,170
Now, the one who is of faith shares with the person who craves the idea of wanting.

53
00:07:27,571 --> 00:07:31,896
But, of course, the wanting here is more skillful, more wholesome.

54
00:07:32,276 --> 00:07:35,221
They really want the Dharma, you see.

55
00:07:35,240 --> 00:07:36,401
And this is...

56
00:07:37,158 --> 00:07:38,279
the description of one.

57
00:07:38,901 --> 00:07:43,971
This is taken from the, as some of you know, the Visuddhimagga, which is later medieval commentary.

58
00:07:44,952 --> 00:08:00,482
In one of faithful temperament, there is frequent occurrence of such states as free generosity, desire to see noble ones, desire to hear good dharma, great gladness, ingenuousness, honesty, and trust in things that inspire trust.

59
00:08:02,437 --> 00:08:24,242
so it's the sort of person who just is ready to submit or to give themselves to the teaching without question based on that faith and my experience with eastern teachers is that that's really your relationship to them

60
00:08:25,538 --> 00:08:35,687
If I were to ask, say, one of my teachers, a janitor or somebody, a question as to why are we watching the breath of the nose, he'd sort of be miffed.

61
00:08:37,470 --> 00:08:38,429
What do you want an app for?

62
00:08:39,010 --> 00:08:39,511
Just do it.

63
00:08:43,355 --> 00:08:51,342
And one of the great criticisms of Eastern teachers towards Westerners was that they didn't have faith.

64
00:08:53,145 --> 00:08:56,751
And what they meant was this unquestioning reliance upon a teacher.

65
00:08:57,633 --> 00:09:18,304
Now, you can imagine, if you're born into a culture, and you're imbued with that culture, and there you have a teacher in front of you, a monk or layperson, whoever, and when they speak, they're part of that tradition, so there's no idea of actually questioning them as such.

66
00:09:18,325 --> 00:09:18,445
Right?

67
00:09:20,736 --> 00:09:24,100
The danger, of course, is gullibility.

68
00:09:24,181 --> 00:09:24,942
I mean, you get led.

69
00:09:24,961 --> 00:09:32,990
I mean, so many Westerners who fall into the trap of the guru find themselves being led all over the place.

70
00:09:33,370 --> 00:09:46,524
Of course, they tell you in Buddhism, in the actual guru tradition of Tibet, that in Tibet people take years to decide whether this person is going to be their guru or not.

71
00:09:46,774 --> 00:09:48,057
How true that is, I don't know.

72
00:09:49,038 --> 00:09:56,931
But there is a type of westerner who really wants that sort of relationship.

73
00:09:58,653 --> 00:10:13,996
It's always, even though we've been through our wonderful enlightenment and arrived at this amazing rationality, there's still a surprising number, surprising to me that is, who actually just wants somebody to tell them what to do.

74
00:10:14,753 --> 00:10:16,754
You know, just do this, do that, and I'll be happy.

75
00:10:20,080 --> 00:10:28,129
Now, to support this in the Buddha's time, of somebody who had just this utter faith, was a man called Chulapantika.

76
00:10:28,929 --> 00:10:33,475
Now, Chulapantika had a brother called Mahapantika, which means big pantika.

77
00:10:33,495 --> 00:10:37,201
He was Chul, he was lesser, he was a lesser pantika.

78
00:10:37,221 --> 00:10:43,207
And his brother had joined the order, and then asked his younger brother to join him.

79
00:10:43,407 --> 00:10:50,216
So his younger brother joined, and after four months, he hadn't learnt a single verse of the Buddha's teachings.

80
00:10:50,615 --> 00:10:52,278
So his brother said, you'd better get out.

81
00:10:52,999 --> 00:10:53,580
You wasted time.

82
00:10:54,660 --> 00:11:00,389
When the Buddha heard this, he went to see him, and urged him not to do that.

83
00:11:00,909 --> 00:11:02,792
And then he gave him this exercise, some of you will know it.

84
00:11:04,073 --> 00:11:09,059
Gave him a piece of cloth, and he told him to wipe his face with the cloth,

85
00:11:11,065 --> 00:11:40,649
and keep saying getting dirty being aware of the change in the cloth as he's wiping it and looking at it remember it's a hot country like we are now and he's wiping his face and he suddenly sees the quality of transience of change and he sees it to such a depth that he becomes enlightened I tried it

86
00:11:44,461 --> 00:11:44,902
Yeah.

87
00:11:48,706 --> 00:11:49,548
He must have been ready.

88
00:11:52,591 --> 00:11:55,575
We can presume he did lots of training in his past life.

89
00:11:56,736 --> 00:12:08,351
But there he was, you see, a person of not particularly bright and just open, just open to the Buddha's suggestion without any question.

90
00:12:09,913 --> 00:12:10,193
You see?

91
00:12:10,615 --> 00:12:13,118
And there comes that insight.

92
00:12:16,101 --> 00:12:36,860
So what I'm saying is that in a society which, shall we say, to somebody who's brought up in a more rational way, in a society where the truth is being expounded, you may be on a winner just having faith.

93
00:12:38,342 --> 00:12:43,947
I mean, if it is the truth, and you have faith and you do the practice, it saves a lot of bother, doesn't it?

94
00:12:44,754 --> 00:12:47,845
You don't have to read books, you don't have to argue, you don't have to ask questions, you just do it.

95
00:12:54,346 --> 00:12:56,875
So that's pre-modern.

96
00:12:57,293 --> 00:13:03,363
in the sense of that sort of ethos, which we have, of course, still here.

97
00:13:03,403 --> 00:13:06,467
I mean, the Catholic Church is very much like that.

98
00:13:07,149 --> 00:13:12,918
And as I say, Buddhism in the East, for Easterners, is very much like that.

99
00:13:13,759 --> 00:13:23,756
The younger generation who are brought up in the horror of rationalizing do question, very disconcerting,

100
00:13:26,403 --> 00:13:32,714
Now, the next, the rejection of that, of course, was modernism.

101
00:13:33,976 --> 00:13:38,644
And the core of the modernist movement was the Enlightenment.

102
00:13:40,128 --> 00:13:49,524
And I suppose the glory of the modernist movement was the ending of slavery, the demand for equality amongst people, and

103
00:13:51,326 --> 00:13:57,312
The turning towards people, towards society as a measure of truth rather than revelation.

104
00:14:00,495 --> 00:14:08,624
And therefore reason, being able to reason with people and come to a reasonable outcome was the mark of a modernist approach.

105
00:14:10,186 --> 00:14:20,135
And perhaps one of the glories of it is the United Nations Declaration of Human Rights in which I'm pretty sure God is not mentioned.

106
00:14:20,504 --> 00:14:21,664
Revelation is not mentioned.

107
00:14:22,206 --> 00:14:27,231
It's a document which human beings have agreed upon totally through their rational understanding.

108
00:14:33,078 --> 00:14:39,066
You know, the French Revolution, equality, fraternity, what was the other one?

109
00:14:41,288 --> 00:14:42,309
Liberty, thank you.

110
00:14:46,389 --> 00:15:07,316
See, equality, liberty, freedom from, freedom, you know, as we have now, freedom to vote for any political party, freedom of speech, all these freedoms that we enjoy were a huge reaction to the very strict, autocratic, pre-modern society.

111
00:15:07,736 --> 00:15:10,440
A huge revolution, really.

112
00:15:14,234 --> 00:15:22,053
And the downside, of course, was that rationality then became its own servant.

113
00:15:22,115 --> 00:15:25,263
It couldn't, shall we say, look beyond the rational.

114
00:15:25,965 --> 00:15:30,014
And as we know, anything which is rational is always based on a premise.

115
00:15:31,327 --> 00:15:42,058
So if the premise, no matter how wonderful the rationality, no matter how much the argument is, the premise is wrong, then in a sense you're moving towards a peculiar situation.

116
00:15:43,120 --> 00:15:50,167
So communism, you know, Nazism, although Nazism had a lot of, had a romantic streak about it.

117
00:15:53,450 --> 00:15:58,095
So you can see how eventually people became disillusioned.

118
00:15:59,003 --> 00:16:10,976
The other, of course, great gift of modernism was investigation, just that opening of the universe to investigation, our science and eventually our technology.

119
00:16:11,937 --> 00:16:15,621
So all these were the products of that modern mind.

120
00:16:15,662 --> 00:16:19,405
I don't think the pre-modern mind could have done it because they weren't interested.

121
00:16:19,486 --> 00:16:22,529
What they were interested in was just stabilizing society.

122
00:16:24,907 --> 00:16:26,509
The idea of progress.

123
00:16:28,094 --> 00:16:44,788
As far as I've read, I picked up this little bit of information about a monk called Joachim de Fiore, a Calabrian, who came up with the idea, and this was how this idea of progress crept into the West, the idea that we were going somewhere, that we weren't actually static.

124
00:16:45,528 --> 00:16:47,172
He talked about the three ages.

125
00:16:47,472 --> 00:16:50,278
The age of the Father, which was the Old Testament.

126
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:53,287
The age of the Son, which is the present age.

127
00:16:53,967 --> 00:16:55,751
And we're moving towards the age of the Spirit.

128
00:16:57,937 --> 00:17:01,245
Everybody will be, you know, saved.

129
00:17:01,265 --> 00:17:03,991
Here on Earth.

130
00:17:08,511 --> 00:17:17,207
Now, in that sort of society, in terms of your spiritual development, that sort of ethos, the teacher takes a different role and the student has a different role.

131
00:17:17,847 --> 00:17:27,786
Because here we have much more of a Socratic approach, where everything that is given to the student, the student is understood to question.

132
00:17:28,185 --> 00:17:31,531
It must become their knowledge.

133
00:17:32,743 --> 00:17:46,940
Now, I don't know, I mean, I've tried to find somebody whom you might look upon who achieved some sort of enlightenment in the West of some sort who might have been brought up with that.

134
00:17:49,623 --> 00:17:53,646
Maybe, I don't know, does anybody?

135
00:17:54,868 --> 00:17:58,853
You see, because the whole of human effort came off the spiritual

136
00:17:59,676 --> 00:18:05,403
I mean, the whole medieval ages was moving up to the spiritual all the time.

137
00:18:05,482 --> 00:18:10,969
All the music, all the art, all the philosophy and theology was all around.

138
00:18:11,349 --> 00:18:13,571
Christianity was all facing up that way.

139
00:18:14,792 --> 00:18:20,078
With modernism, our whole effort sort of flattened out.

140
00:18:20,179 --> 00:18:22,781
It wasn't so much interested in the spiritual so much.

141
00:18:23,385 --> 00:18:25,748
but more in this investigation.

142
00:18:26,308 --> 00:18:32,976
Not that philosophers like Spinoza and people like that didn't have a spiritual element to it.

143
00:18:36,779 --> 00:18:43,006
Would anyone like to mention somebody they think that who belongs to a modernist ethos who might have achieved?

144
00:18:47,351 --> 00:18:47,711
What about Darwin?

145
00:18:47,730 --> 00:18:49,613
Well, no, I'm thinking of sainthood.

146
00:18:50,690 --> 00:18:58,459
Yeah, somebody who's achieved a spiritual, you would recognize a spiritual, the founder of the Quakers maybe.

147
00:19:01,622 --> 00:19:04,025
He started off from a personal revelation, you see.

148
00:19:04,464 --> 00:19:07,248
So I'm stuck there.

149
00:19:07,387 --> 00:19:10,111
I shall wait for your response afterwards.

150
00:19:14,355 --> 00:19:19,801
Now this relates to the second character type, which is

151
00:19:20,862 --> 00:19:27,334
I mean, it's translated as intelligent, but you'll see from the actual quote that it's not quite the intelligence that we expect.

152
00:19:29,598 --> 00:19:42,903
In one of intelligent temperament, there is frequent occurrence of such states as ready to be spoken to, readiness to be spoken to, possession of good friends, knowledge of the right amount of eating,

153
00:19:44,773 --> 00:19:49,700
Mindfulness and full awareness, that's mindfulness and full awareness in task, in what we're doing.

154
00:19:50,641 --> 00:19:51,942
Devotion to wakefulness.

155
00:19:53,344 --> 00:19:57,868
A sense of urgency about things that should inspire a sense of urgency.

156
00:19:58,769 --> 00:20:00,491
And wisely directed endeavour.

157
00:20:02,535 --> 00:20:09,083
So here you get the impression that this person is constantly reflecting wisely upon their lives.

158
00:20:09,222 --> 00:20:10,324
They're actually engaged.

159
00:20:10,564 --> 00:20:13,768
They're not there with a teacher who says, do this, do that.

160
00:20:14,136 --> 00:20:19,945
They're turning upon themselves as, in a sense, the source of their own wisdom.

161
00:20:20,527 --> 00:20:25,114
Not without the help of the teacher, because they go and visit people.

162
00:20:25,153 --> 00:20:26,856
Possession of good friends.

163
00:20:32,204 --> 00:20:33,567
Readiness to be spoken to.

164
00:20:33,607 --> 00:20:36,251
There's no actual teacher mentioned as such.

165
00:20:37,894 --> 00:20:39,576
I suppose readiness to be spoken to.

166
00:20:40,077 --> 00:20:40,818
I suppose that's it.

167
00:20:44,191 --> 00:20:54,644
So such a person has that inner reasoning to be able to understand their own position and has a confidence in it.

168
00:20:54,845 --> 00:21:09,304
In the scriptures, the Buddha is often in that sort of position where he actually takes on a sort of Socratic role where he asks, what do you think, what do you think, you know.

169
00:21:10,786 --> 00:21:12,508
He said, does everything arise and pass away?

170
00:21:12,909 --> 00:21:14,049
Yes, Bhante.

171
00:21:14,069 --> 00:21:17,213
If it arises and passes away, is that satisfactory?

172
00:21:17,555 --> 00:21:20,459
No, Bhante.

173
00:21:20,479 --> 00:21:25,164
It's all pretty simple stuff from our point of view, but it's there as a sort of dialogue.

174
00:21:25,204 --> 00:21:26,846
He's not saying everything passes away.

175
00:21:26,886 --> 00:21:35,999
And it's that part of the scripture that seems to come across to Westerners.

176
00:21:36,519 --> 00:21:40,084
So we tend to think of Buddhism as very highly rational in that sense.

177
00:21:43,944 --> 00:21:50,652
There is an example of somebody and he was called by the Buddha Tucha Potila.

178
00:21:51,113 --> 00:21:52,094
And Tucha means empty.

179
00:21:52,513 --> 00:21:57,778
Now Potila was a teacher and somebody who was recognized and understood the Buddha's teaching.

180
00:21:57,839 --> 00:21:59,902
He could really talk about it.

181
00:21:59,922 --> 00:22:01,723
But he hadn't experienced anything.

182
00:22:01,743 --> 00:22:02,904
So the Buddha called him empty.

183
00:22:03,285 --> 00:22:04,046
Empty Potila.

184
00:22:05,166 --> 00:22:11,673
And he got rather worried that the people whom he taught were all becoming enlightened and he wasn't.

185
00:22:12,076 --> 00:22:23,169
So, swallowing the bitter pill of humility, he went off to his students and they saw him coming and immediately saw this intellectual conceit.

186
00:22:24,290 --> 00:22:27,013
They thought, well, there's no way I can get through this.

187
00:22:27,034 --> 00:22:30,077
So they passed him on down the line saying, well, I'm not really the right one.

188
00:22:30,659 --> 00:22:38,488
And he ended up with a young seminarian boy, a little monk.

189
00:22:39,582 --> 00:22:50,807
and again swallowing his pride he went and followed this little fellow who took him to an anthill and he said to him

190
00:22:51,361 --> 00:23:01,672
If there are six holes in this anthill, and there's a lizard or a snake in there, if an anthill's vacated, in the East, lizards, sometimes snakes, live in anthills, how would you get the snake out?

191
00:23:01,932 --> 00:23:03,574
He said, well, you stop at five holes.

192
00:23:05,195 --> 00:23:07,337
And the little boy said to him, that's what you must do.

193
00:23:07,357 --> 00:23:13,924
He says, you must stop up the five senses and observe the mind, observe the heart, you see.

194
00:23:13,944 --> 00:23:18,329
Well, as the story always goes, in no length of time...

195
00:23:18,799 --> 00:23:21,890
Tuchaputila became one of the Arahats.

196
00:23:29,874 --> 00:23:31,137
One of the...

197
00:23:32,012 --> 00:23:58,662
paradoxes should we say, no one of the actual straight contradictions that you'll find people get into in Buddhism is this especially on the monastic side because what makes the monastic order is the rule it's an institution so it's the rules of the institution that make you a monastic

198
00:23:59,721 --> 00:24:04,166
And I've come across this quite a few times in the East, mainly Westerners.

199
00:24:04,587 --> 00:24:05,769
Easterners don't seem to have a problem with it.

200
00:24:06,509 --> 00:24:07,711
It's the case of this.

201
00:24:09,594 --> 00:24:13,919
In order to be enlightened, you have to be pure of heart.

202
00:24:15,480 --> 00:24:19,986
But you can't be pure of heart totally unless you're fully enlightened.

203
00:24:21,346 --> 00:24:27,855
So people get themselves into this corner and if they've been meditating for some time,

204
00:24:29,287 --> 00:24:34,532
then they think that it must be because they're not keeping the rule strictly.

205
00:24:35,373 --> 00:24:37,496
In other words, they're not pure in the rule.

206
00:24:38,497 --> 00:24:41,960
So they get tighter and tighter and tighter around the rule.

207
00:24:43,362 --> 00:24:45,003
And we had one case in Sri Lanka.

208
00:24:48,728 --> 00:24:50,548
An Australian fellow.

209
00:24:50,569 --> 00:24:52,491
And he went back to the original text.

210
00:24:53,593 --> 00:24:58,617
And he realized that the robes that we're wearing now, these robes, were not

211
00:24:59,019 --> 00:25:28,082
the robes that the Buddha had started with all those many years ago the top robe was just like a shawl you put over your shoulders when you went into a city sort of like a modesty thing generally speaking you just use the lower robe so he went to see a very famous teacher some of you will know him Ananda Maitreya of Balangoda some of you know him he died 150

212
00:25:28,500 --> 00:25:48,096
and he was a Bodhisattva during one of his meditations at the monastery I was at in Khandaboda as you progress there comes a point where some deep memory may arise and he remembered being in the Buddhist time and making the vow to become a Buddha

213
00:25:48,633 --> 00:26:18,066
so he was known as the Bodhisattva he said he could remember the faces of Sariputta and Moggallana the two main disciples of the Buddha but he couldn't remember the Buddha's face unfortunately when you make that sort of determination in Theravada Buddhism I don't know about Mahayana it means you can't progress you've got to keep building up your virtues until you're right on the point of enlightenment

214
00:26:18,316 --> 00:26:24,862
And then, when you take your next re-roll, you have to do it all in that one go, in that one lifetime.

215
00:26:27,183 --> 00:26:37,173
So, he went to, this particular monk, went to see him, and Ananda Maitreya agreed that, in fact, the lower rope was that.

216
00:26:37,753 --> 00:26:38,855
And the bowl was wrong.

217
00:26:39,756 --> 00:26:45,561
If you've seen monks' bowls, they're pretty big, you know.

218
00:26:45,582 --> 00:26:47,884
And, in fact, they're supposed to be just...

219
00:26:49,805 --> 00:26:52,509
I had a little embarrassing moment over that.

220
00:26:52,868 --> 00:26:59,577
I was in India and I was at Goenkaji Centre in Damagiri, near Bombay.

221
00:27:00,700 --> 00:27:03,884
And we were lining up for food and with me there was a Jain monk.

222
00:27:05,446 --> 00:27:09,152
And he had a bowl, it was very small, like that.

223
00:27:09,172 --> 00:27:15,420
And I made a rather foolish comment and said, Bhante, that's a very small bowl.

224
00:27:15,941 --> 00:27:19,625
And he looked at me and he said, this is the size of my stomach.

225
00:27:21,007 --> 00:27:25,433
And I was there.

226
00:27:25,453 --> 00:27:32,486
So I made this sort of limp excuse about it also being the place I put my robes in because it's my luggage case.

227
00:27:34,829 --> 00:27:36,653
Yes, he didn't look all that convinced.

228
00:27:39,817 --> 00:27:47,250
And he turned up, this particular monk, at the Katina ceremony, which is the ceremony at the end of the

229
00:27:47,652 --> 00:28:15,262
range retreat that monks do where they have to stay in one monastery at the end all the lay people come offering gifts for what the monastery and the monks might need and he turned up with this twee little cape tied up around his neck looked like a bullfighter and a biscuit tin sweet bowl and the general opinion was that he'd gone mad

230
00:28:18,314 --> 00:28:46,818
and he eventually drove himself out of the order so you know rationality but it would seem from the story of Tucha Potila that if a person is completely blocked into a way of being in the world which is so totally rational so totally conceptual

231
00:28:49,329 --> 00:28:54,616
that somehow the person has the intelligence to become enlightened.

232
00:28:54,676 --> 00:28:55,438
That's not the problem.

233
00:28:55,817 --> 00:29:01,405
The problem is to evacuate that situation of intelligence.

234
00:29:01,625 --> 00:29:13,161
And one of the things that, for instance, Dzogchen, we had Sotni Rinpoche come down to Gaia House to give a retreat.

235
00:29:14,136 --> 00:29:32,621
One of the things that he was trying to do was just so relax people, make them feel so happy, make them feel so, you know, that with a couple of exercises, this original mind would just pop out from that embeddement in rationality.

236
00:29:33,501 --> 00:29:36,105
And the person might just realize their true self, you see.

237
00:29:40,570 --> 00:29:42,252
We do it the hard way in Theravada.

238
00:29:44,106 --> 00:30:13,336
sweat so that's the modern society based on reason whether I mean most of us most of us are brought up with that mindset so that's our problem when we start training in the spiritual life is to find a way of coming out of conceptual thinking

239
00:30:15,426 --> 00:30:34,872
So, for instance, in the methodology that I personally teach, which is the mahasis, my own particular practice too, we try to trick the mind by refusing to allow it to think about something, save in the simplest of concepts.

240
00:30:35,712 --> 00:30:38,076
So we engage that intellect

241
00:30:38,241 --> 00:30:58,815
through a noting technique rising, falling so when there's only one word there at least there can't be a thinking about the object at least there's only one, shall we say, concept between that intelligence and the direct perception of what it's trying to experience

242
00:31:00,617 --> 00:31:14,461
And then as the concentration grows, you see, and the ability of that mind to stay absolutely within the present moment, there isn't the time for thought, because thought's always an afterthought, always a comment.

243
00:31:16,785 --> 00:31:21,613
And by force of that practice and concentration, suddenly,

244
00:31:22,807 --> 00:31:24,289
that intellect will just stop.

245
00:31:25,030 --> 00:31:27,394
And then you have that brightness of pure awareness.

246
00:31:28,295 --> 00:31:32,842
And hopefully, in no length of time, we join the Adahats.

247
00:31:37,548 --> 00:31:41,012
So now, we come to post-modernism.

248
00:31:42,233 --> 00:31:43,135
Now, I haven't a clue.

249
00:31:43,175 --> 00:31:46,740
I've read little bits about it.

250
00:31:47,280 --> 00:31:50,065
As far as I understand it,

251
00:31:51,142 --> 00:32:20,945
post-modernism is a rejection of modernism and actually historically speaking the first rejection of modernism was romanticism it was people like I suppose Rousseau and Wordsworth and all our poets who sort of went back to feeling and sensual experience took that as the basis of truth not thought I think therefore I am I feel I sense therefore I am

252
00:32:21,736 --> 00:32:29,688
And the problem with Romanticism is, of course, that it couldn't accept the present.

253
00:32:30,128 --> 00:32:35,155
It looked back into the past for its inspiration.

254
00:32:35,757 --> 00:32:39,262
The noble savage idea, Garden of Eden, you see.

255
00:32:39,923 --> 00:32:47,355
And in present day, you know, there's certain feminists who look back to a matriarchal age as being...

256
00:32:47,722 --> 00:32:55,479
as being better, would have been better than a patriarchal age, a sort of reaching into the past, a sort of nostalgia.

257
00:32:57,282 --> 00:33:06,541
I read somewhere that the masculine, then there was some sort of deep ecology, that's inverted commas, going back to hunters and gatherers, you know.

258
00:33:10,471 --> 00:33:17,501
But the idea of running around with a sort of dog pelt around with privates chasing rabbits didn't particularly appeal.

259
00:33:19,605 --> 00:33:24,192
So what happened there was there was no particular practice to go back to.

260
00:33:24,211 --> 00:33:30,521
It sort of expressed itself more in terms of art.

261
00:33:31,867 --> 00:33:40,656
I don't know whether it produced any, I can't think of anybody it produced whom you might look to as a spiritual figure as such, although it was spiritually directed.

262
00:33:43,880 --> 00:33:57,133
As that faded out, the reaction to romanticism, but also in a sense a reaction to pure reason, was the idealism, people like Hegel and Fichte.

263
00:33:58,311 --> 00:34:07,730
And the bits I've read of these philosophers, they definitely had a very highly tuned idea of the growth of consciousness.

264
00:34:08,532 --> 00:34:12,079
It seems to relate in many ways to Buddhism.

265
00:34:13,501 --> 00:34:17,990
But I think the downfall for those people seems to have been they didn't have a practice.

266
00:34:19,827 --> 00:34:48,146
the philosopher Fichte said to his students to face a wall and become aware of the observer and then to become aware of that that doesn't sound so bad actually but that was the it was all very heady it was all wonderful ideas and very inspirational but there was no practice to it so it seems as though people got fed up with that

267
00:34:53,105 --> 00:34:55,547
So then, of course, modernism really took hold.

268
00:34:55,967 --> 00:35:01,375
And that's where we ended up with the Second World War and all that sort of stuff.

269
00:35:01,394 --> 00:35:14,329
So after the Second World War and communism and all that, then we have this other modern strain of rejection of modernism, which we call postmodern.

270
00:35:15,271 --> 00:35:18,173
It comes to be called postmodern anyway.

271
00:35:18,193 --> 00:35:20,817
And I don't know whether you'd agree with me, but

272
00:35:21,590 --> 00:35:26,675
the crucial position for a post-modernist is interpretation.

273
00:35:27,856 --> 00:35:33,164
So, before, it was revelation, it was out there, it was it, it was given.

274
00:35:33,184 --> 00:35:41,313
Then it was we, as rational beings, conversing to come to understand the truth together.

275
00:35:42,675 --> 00:35:46,099
Since both of those has failed, I'm now reverting to me.

276
00:35:46,139 --> 00:35:50,583
So I am now the fount of my own truth.

277
00:35:51,458 --> 00:36:16,503
and you are for you and if we don't agree that's fine see what's true for you is true for you don't have to be true for me and so we move towards a sort of absolute relativism so there's no objective truth at all it's just what's true for you so Noddy is important as much as Shakespeare the book's on Noddy because it depends where you are you see

278
00:36:17,260 --> 00:36:20,023
There's no objective reality.

279
00:36:20,422 --> 00:36:34,378
I read an article which said that the 7-11 collapse of the Twin Towers put an end to post-modernism because there was no doubt there from a societal point of view that that was something which was objective and it did happen.

280
00:36:35,940 --> 00:36:43,807
It was through this post-modernist thinking that people could undermine the idea that there was ever a holocaust.

281
00:36:45,103 --> 00:36:46,686
Because it's your take on reality.

282
00:36:47,128 --> 00:36:48,010
It's your narrative.

283
00:36:48,090 --> 00:36:48,731
That's the word, isn't it?

284
00:36:48,751 --> 00:36:49,612
It's your narrative.

285
00:36:50,233 --> 00:36:53,139
And a society builds up its own narrative for its own purposes.

286
00:36:55,284 --> 00:37:04,782
And once you catch that in fact there's no objective truth to it, then of course it collapses as science, as truth.

287
00:37:11,699 --> 00:37:15,382
In society, it's very strange.

288
00:37:15,884 --> 00:37:32,764
When I went to Gaia House, it was a very strange place for me because I'd always been brought up in modernist societies and the order is almost pre-modern really in many aspects in terms of its authority structure.

289
00:37:34,967 --> 00:37:37,690
But when I got to Gaia, I found that there were these

290
00:37:38,378 --> 00:37:44,186
centers of authority who were making decisions without others sort of knowing.

291
00:37:44,226 --> 00:37:44,967
It was a sort of...

292
00:37:46,768 --> 00:37:47,829
It was all very strange.

293
00:37:49,893 --> 00:37:51,034
Things happened, you know.

294
00:37:53,777 --> 00:38:05,853
Just recently, for instance, a huge armchair arrived in the lounge and the managing director, the executive manager,

295
00:38:06,204 --> 00:38:30,777
didn't know about it it just this big thing arrived and she looked round I was in the room with her so what happens is that since I am now the centre of authority we're all centres of authority and when a society has no centre

296
00:38:31,467 --> 00:39:00,141
you can do what you do because it's right for you and I can do what I do because it's right for me and you've no right to stop me at all it's a sort of movement towards anarchism in its absolute true sense and a friend of mine told me about a lovely post-modern situation that they found themselves in they'd been invited to a meal with two friends and they went there to the house he and his partner to this couple's house

297
00:39:00,577 --> 00:39:19,297
And while they were having a meal, sorry, after the meal, they were sitting in the lounge, just enjoying the postprandial discussions and all that sort of stuff, when the lodger, a woman, came down, started doing yoga right there in the nude.

298
00:39:21,840 --> 00:39:25,382
And they said to her, you know, is this appropriate?

299
00:39:26,585 --> 00:39:28,947
Well, you do what you do and I'll do what I like.

300
00:39:31,340 --> 00:39:33,563
And it's that me generation, you know.

301
00:39:33,623 --> 00:39:44,034
I've noticed that Gaia, anybody in their 30s is very different from somebody in their 50s, which is, of course, where I am.

302
00:39:44,054 --> 00:39:47,559
In their 50s, you'll still get people talking about responsibility.

303
00:39:48,179 --> 00:39:50,141
In their 30s, they're talking about rights.

304
00:39:52,625 --> 00:39:54,266
My rights, it's weird.

305
00:39:54,286 --> 00:39:55,809
And, of course, the clash is wonderful.

306
00:39:59,592 --> 00:40:01,195
I went on a walk with...

307
00:40:01,697 --> 00:40:05,623
the managers at Gaia, who tend to be postmodern in this sense.

308
00:40:06,704 --> 00:40:21,425
Because, and it's understandable in one sense, because they come from anywhere to offer a year of their lives to the Dharma and end up with people whom they would normally not choose to live with.

309
00:40:21,445 --> 00:40:25,731
And so you have a group of people who have to sort of live communally

310
00:40:26,182 --> 00:40:32,590
But the structure there doesn't really allow a community because people are moving in and out so often.

311
00:40:32,811 --> 00:40:38,579
Every six months it's like being at a railway station.

312
00:40:38,599 --> 00:40:54,097
So living in that sort of community you tend to get people who are very fierce about their position and try to come to a consensuality.

313
00:40:55,764 --> 00:41:04,096
And the problem with consensuality is that if everybody has a right, then everybody has a right to veto.

314
00:41:05,217 --> 00:41:09,103
So even though seven people say they'll do it, if somebody says no, you've had it.

315
00:41:09,802 --> 00:41:10,605
You can't move.

316
00:41:11,085 --> 00:41:15,090
So they come to an agreement that nobody has an actual veto.

317
00:41:15,110 --> 00:41:16,592
They can have a majority rule, I think.

318
00:41:18,335 --> 00:41:19,315
And we went out for a walk.

319
00:41:19,356 --> 00:41:20,878
I went out for a walk with a few of them.

320
00:41:21,449 --> 00:41:47,742
and we were going to go to this riverside which somebody said was absolutely beautiful and we have a picnic there and on the way over a dell down in the bottom we came across a very delightful little stream and one of the party said I want to stay here see and everybody else said well we were going over there no this is where the group begins to control the individual

321
00:41:49,056 --> 00:41:49,737
That's what they felt.

322
00:41:50,038 --> 00:41:51,780
Controlled individual, you see.

323
00:41:51,800 --> 00:41:52,721
So we went, well, fine.

324
00:41:52,740 --> 00:41:53,302
You stay here.

325
00:41:54,563 --> 00:42:00,449
So then we had to share the food and she ended up with the orange juice.

326
00:42:03,313 --> 00:42:04,594
And we had to do without the orange juice.

327
00:42:07,157 --> 00:42:08,280
Because we all had it in one bottle.

328
00:42:11,222 --> 00:42:11,583
Wonderful.

329
00:42:15,307 --> 00:42:18,050
So now we have a big problem, you see.

330
00:42:22,367 --> 00:42:24,211
Oh yes, sorry, that's right.

331
00:42:26,896 --> 00:42:31,405
I've got a lovely description of art, which gives you an idea.

332
00:42:31,925 --> 00:42:40,242
A rejection of a consistent, coherent aesthetic in favour of a playful, eclectic style which draws on many sources.

333
00:42:43,005 --> 00:42:49,873
So in other words, the artist feels free to use whatever, however they want.

334
00:42:49,893 --> 00:43:05,351
And often, as I'm sure some of you have experienced, especially in modern art, very modern art, the artist is really looking to symbols which often make sense to them, but they don't have that objective aspect.

335
00:43:06,512 --> 00:43:33,903
position where people can relate to it this way so it's Eliot who said art was objective correlative so I have an experience I want to relate it to you and I choose an object through which we can make that communication now if I choose an object which is meaningless to you but full of meaning to me and the communication then stops although the artist could argue well you should make the effort

336
00:43:34,188 --> 00:43:38,132
you know, to come towards me, to try and understand this symbology, you see.

337
00:43:44,161 --> 00:43:47,125
So now we have the problem of the role of the teacher.

338
00:43:47,905 --> 00:43:52,172
Well, you can see that there can't be a teacher.

339
00:43:52,192 --> 00:43:56,297
Because if a teacher says to you, listen, I think...

340
00:43:57,003 --> 00:44:09,798
you ought to do, you know, like they're saying, well, your meditation's not so good, and it's because, you know, you're not working on this particular... See, the student will reply, well, that's true for you.

341
00:44:12,041 --> 00:44:13,702
But it's not, that's not the way I see things.

342
00:44:15,105 --> 00:44:17,128
How do you get anywhere with that sort of relationship?

343
00:44:21,873 --> 00:44:26,418
So, and the student, of course, feels an authority unto themselves...

344
00:44:26,887 --> 00:44:30,110
Only taking little bits from what they want from different traditions.

345
00:44:30,492 --> 00:44:32,474
Building up their own little eclectic style.

346
00:44:34,496 --> 00:44:34,916
Yeah?

347
00:44:34,936 --> 00:44:38,298
You've all come across those, eh?

348
00:44:38,338 --> 00:44:43,844
So you have a bit of yoga and a bit of tai chi and a bit of vipassana, a bit of zogchen.

349
00:44:43,864 --> 00:44:44,706
Get it all in, you see.

350
00:44:45,226 --> 00:44:46,407
And you decide what you're going to do.

351
00:44:46,768 --> 00:44:55,916
And unless you're very, very spiritually inclined, unless there's a clarity in your mind, then you end up with quite a lot of confusion in your spiritual practice.

352
00:44:59,574 --> 00:45:06,786
Now in these character types, there's what's called the confused or the speculative type.

353
00:45:07,106 --> 00:45:09,650
And this is the description.

354
00:45:09,670 --> 00:45:25,954
In one of speculative temperament, there is a frequent occurrence of such states as talkativeness, sociability, boredom with devotion to the profitable, failure to finish undertakings,

355
00:45:27,182 --> 00:45:29,746
Smoking by day and flaming by night.

356
00:45:33,610 --> 00:45:35,291
And mental running hither and thither.

357
00:45:36,813 --> 00:45:40,057
The smoking by day is planning...

358
00:45:40,077 --> 00:45:46,103
Sorry, the smoking by night is planning and scheming.

359
00:45:47,206 --> 00:45:49,507
Flaming by day is running around doing.

360
00:45:51,090 --> 00:45:51,891
Does that sound...

361
00:45:54,351 --> 00:46:19,650
so that's the speculative type and perhaps also open to skepticism because of that open to skepticism which is that inability to commit yourself entirely to a particular way or path because

362
00:46:20,440 --> 00:46:23,884
You know, you've only got your own reason, your own particular experience to go on.

363
00:46:23,903 --> 00:46:27,967
You're not prepared to put faith either in a person or in a tradition.

364
00:46:29,269 --> 00:46:32,572
Either to revelation or to somebody else's guidance.

365
00:46:35,556 --> 00:46:38,278
So, there's a huge danger there.

366
00:46:38,519 --> 00:46:43,704
And yet, we have in Buddhism this idea of a Pachaka Buddha.

367
00:46:44,666 --> 00:46:47,949
Now, a Pachaka Buddha is translated as a private Buddha.

368
00:46:48,840 --> 00:46:53,427
What it's saying is that some people become enlightened but can't teach.

369
00:46:56,190 --> 00:47:00,295
There's a hint that people become enlightened there in other forms, in other traditions.

370
00:47:01,255 --> 00:47:04,539
But it's this kernel thing that they can't teach.

371
00:47:05,601 --> 00:47:08,585
That's very post-modern, isn't it?

372
00:47:08,606 --> 00:47:12,250
Because this person has made their way through their own paths

373
00:47:13,360 --> 00:47:20,827
And in a sense, because it's not part of a tradition, because they've ended up, in a sense, in their own private way.

374
00:47:24,291 --> 00:47:27,255
How far they can't teach, I don't know, but it says they can't teach.

375
00:47:27,815 --> 00:47:43,231
Now, one of the amazing things about the spiritual scene today, these days, is the arrival of these independently enlightened beings.

376
00:47:44,731 --> 00:48:10,114
Rajneesh Krishnamurti recently the flavouring month is Eckhart Tolle Stephen who am I thinking of what is Enlightenment magazine Andrew Cohen Ken Wilber interesting isn't it

377
00:48:11,039 --> 00:48:13,221
These people, of course, do have a teaching.

378
00:48:13,400 --> 00:48:16,503
Dada free John.

379
00:48:18,905 --> 00:48:30,717
So these people do have, and if you read their stuff, they've obviously had some experience, but not within a particular tradition, or at least they might have touched upon a tradition, but they've had something which is peculiar to them.

380
00:48:31,458 --> 00:48:35,202
And then somehow, I mean, in their sense, of course, they do have a following.

381
00:48:36,001 --> 00:48:39,965
But I dare say there are some people who are enlightened, but simply can't.

382
00:48:40,485 --> 00:49:05,193
can't get it across or maybe don't even want it just happy being enlightened I'd be that so now having sort of discussed these three types of societies we say types of ethos call it what you wish pre-modern modern and post-modern really

383
00:49:06,389 --> 00:49:13,481
just to try and see what the Buddha's teaching is in terms of the practice.

384
00:49:21,036 --> 00:49:24,802
There are two occasions where he's talking to an ānda.

385
00:49:28,309 --> 00:49:32,275
The first one is when he's dying during his last few days.

386
00:49:33,195 --> 00:49:37,242
And Ānanda's getting a bit worried as to who will lead the order.

387
00:49:39,063 --> 00:49:43,188
So he asks the Buddha who will he appoint to lead the order.

388
00:49:44,791 --> 00:49:47,414
And his two main disciples have died.

389
00:49:47,934 --> 00:50:16,356
Sariputta died shortly before his own death and Moggallana was murdered by thieves on some path or other so his two main disciples who he perhaps might have handed on his leadership to had died but his response is I'm not going to leave anybody you should live as islands unto yourselves

390
00:50:17,382 --> 00:50:47,068
being your own refuge with no one else as your refuge that's very post-modern isn't it but then in the same breath he says you should live with the Dharma as an island with the Dharma as your refuge with no other refuge now that's revelation that's his revelation to the world he revealed that to the world that's very pre-modern isn't it and then there's um

391
00:50:49,798 --> 00:51:18,034
another occasion where Ananda is walking with him he seems to be doing this all the time Ananda always says to him I think I've understood this and the Buddha says no he doesn't it's sort of humorous really and there's one occasion when he says to the Buddha in my opinion the spiritual livelihood is sorry half

392
00:51:18,469 --> 00:51:22,356
The spiritual livelihood is good friendship, is good community.

393
00:51:22,657 --> 00:51:30,932
And the Buddha says, oh no, the whole of the spiritual life is good companionship, good community.

394
00:51:30,952 --> 00:51:35,681
In other words, to be with people who can, as it were, balance your own views.

395
00:51:37,465 --> 00:51:39,668
Which would suggest a very modern approach.

396
00:51:40,210 --> 00:51:41,052
And when you...

397
00:51:41,538 --> 00:51:51,313
when you couple that with the way he would teach, this sort of Socratic way, then you can see he's also got the modernist perspective in there.

398
00:51:53,896 --> 00:51:58,925
So, I don't quite know where that leaves us, really.

399
00:51:59,045 --> 00:52:05,976
It's really just open to people to have some thoughts around that.

400
00:52:08,807 --> 00:52:27,777
There's also here I've written the Kalama Sutta, which is almost a declaration of free thought, which is a declaration of free thought, where he turns up at a village, at the Kalamas, and they complain, they say, look, this guru comes along and he says this, and then the next guru comes and says, well, he's a load of rubbish, this is what the truth is, what are we supposed to believe, you see.

401
00:52:27,757 --> 00:52:51,807
and he goes through a whole list of things don't believe something just because it's tradition because it makes sense rationally because somebody with great authority has said so and so on and so forth but only when you've experienced it as being true for yourself now the last thought that I had was whenever

402
00:52:52,311 --> 00:53:21,188
society or whenever we make one of these three things the end all and be all of our spiritual practice whether it be the written statement or revelation whether it be reason or whether it be my own personal experience it always subordinates the other two to that one so if you're going to believe in what the Buddha said

403
00:53:21,539 --> 00:53:27,826
then reason is subdued, it goes out the window almost, and your own self goes out.

404
00:53:29,347 --> 00:53:35,695
If you say that you've got to be reasonable, then in a sense there comes an undermining of faith in the revelation.

405
00:53:38,617 --> 00:53:46,246
And if you put yourself first, then you've almost undermined everything in a sense, because you yourself become the centre of authority.

406
00:53:47,375 --> 00:53:57,980
So if a person is deluding themselves into a statement, a belief, it's very difficult for them to get out of that little box they've put themselves into.

407
00:54:00,606 --> 00:54:05,416
So it's only when we have something which, shall we say, reaches beyond

408
00:54:06,257 --> 00:54:13,768
the revelation, the rationality and self, where I think we might be able to get this balance of these three.

409
00:54:14,208 --> 00:54:17,273
So there's the Buddha's word, which is a touchstone.

410
00:54:19,536 --> 00:54:20,699
Then there's our reasoning.

411
00:54:21,599 --> 00:54:23,742
And then there's our own personal experience.

412
00:54:25,123 --> 00:54:31,746
And that personal experience can only come through actual practice, not through thought, through a basic personal practice.

413
00:54:32,306 --> 00:54:36,501
And this is the way the Buddha actually puts the growth of wisdom.

414
00:54:36,835 --> 00:55:01,003
first of all you gain wisdom by what you've heard then as you take that wisdom in and you think about it it becomes your understanding your own thought understanding but it's still at the thought level and it's only then when you turn to the practice and you directly experience wisdom

415
00:55:01,304 --> 00:55:08,213
the truth that the Buddha is talking about, that it becomes vipassana, my opinion, which is the insight knowledge.

416
00:55:11,777 --> 00:55:23,311
So I suppose it's a case of not leaning too heavily on these three things, either the Buddha word or rationality or oneself as a central authority.

417
00:55:32,422 --> 00:55:52,481
Now's the time for tomatoes and eggs.

418
00:55:52,501 --> 00:55:53,963
I spoke for one hour.

419
00:55:54,023 --> 00:55:54,623
That's terrible.

420
00:55:56,806 --> 00:56:00,349
Anybody got any thoughts around that?

421
00:56:00,429 --> 00:56:00,909
Any...

422
00:56:12,652 --> 00:56:19,719
I suppose really what led me to think about this was, you know, like, what happens after post-modernism?

423
00:56:21,260 --> 00:56:23,543
Where do you go after that?

424
00:56:25,385 --> 00:56:27,668
I suppose you have to wait and see.

425
00:56:32,291 --> 00:56:33,914
Well, that's what happens, isn't it, you see?

426
00:56:33,954 --> 00:56:37,117
It's too scary, so they become fundamentalists.

427
00:56:38,639 --> 00:56:39,519
Yeah, that is scary.

428
00:56:43,280 --> 00:57:02,132
we do your own thing in your own way in your own time

429
00:57:05,402 --> 00:57:06,643
Yeah, absolutely.

430
00:57:06,664 --> 00:57:08,806
I think that's what attracts a lot of people.

431
00:57:12,009 --> 00:57:13,831
I think that's what attracts a lot of people in the West.

432
00:57:15,632 --> 00:57:20,677
It's surprising how many people don't want to call themselves Buddhists.

433
00:57:20,697 --> 00:57:21,639
They don't want the label.

434
00:57:21,978 --> 00:57:27,545
And what it suggests to me is they don't want to be part of that tradition as well.

435
00:57:27,684 --> 00:57:28,985
They don't want to be labelled.

436
00:57:29,005 --> 00:57:30,987
I mean, they're happy to be called socialists.

437
00:57:33,061 --> 00:57:38,367
When it comes to spirituality, it's like putting on, they feel like a straitjacket or something.

438
00:57:40,289 --> 00:57:41,449
Something happens to them.

439
00:57:43,052 --> 00:57:44,994
It's as though they give up their autonomy or something.

440
00:57:46,655 --> 00:57:49,239
Who doesn't like to call themselves a Buddhist but does Buddhist practice?

441
00:57:49,438 --> 00:57:52,262
Perhaps you can explain.

442
00:57:52,282 --> 00:57:56,706
So why don't you call yourself a Buddhist?

443
00:57:56,726 --> 00:58:01,211
I think because for me it's like then I'd have to accept all these things and I'd have to believe them all.

444
00:58:01,461 --> 00:58:15,132
That's very interesting because the whole of the Buddha's position was that you don't believe a word he says.

445
00:58:16,126 --> 00:58:18,871
And that's his basis, you know, that everything is up for grabs.

446
00:58:18,931 --> 00:58:20,112
You've got to prove it true to yourself.

447
00:58:20,974 --> 00:58:23,239
Actually, the early Buddhists never called themselves Buddhists.

448
00:58:23,259 --> 00:58:27,827
I mean, that's a Christian West, you know, that we think, like we used to call Mohammedans.

449
00:58:27,847 --> 00:58:29,449
We called them Mohammedanism.

450
00:58:32,335 --> 00:58:39,248
The early Buddhists called themselves Sadamikas, Sadamma, the followers of the true law.

451
00:58:40,527 --> 00:59:05,757
they didn't I mean the Buddha himself said you know who sees the Dharma sees me who sees me sees the Dharma I mean he was constantly pulling himself out as a personality and laying down the law as he saw it the truth as he saw it but it's interesting that you should feel that because sometimes that's how Buddhism comes across especially in its outer form you know

452
00:59:06,768 --> 00:59:14,782
Sometimes I think there is a bit of a contradiction between you've got to test everything for yourself and you only believe it if you've experienced it.

453
00:59:14,802 --> 00:59:22,777
And on the other hand, well, these are the teachings and really just to keep on experiencing until you too agree that the teachings are right.

454
00:59:23,358 --> 00:59:26,164
So what's the point in testing?

455
00:59:26,184 --> 00:59:30,632
No, it's a very good point because I went through a stage when I thought, hold on, I'm being brainwashed.

456
00:59:31,050 --> 00:59:36,918
Because, you know, like every teacher was saying, I need transience, transience, you know, and I'm thinking, whoa, yeah, transience, and I think, well, hold on.

457
00:59:40,961 --> 00:59:46,369
Yeah, I suppose it's a case of trusting eventually in the experience of your own meditation.

458
00:59:47,550 --> 00:59:56,400
And that will bring you to a direct experience which you don't feel has been conditioned by thought.

459
00:59:56,460 --> 00:59:58,121
That's the important thing.

460
00:59:59,501 --> 01:00:28,023
the person has an experience which they think has been conditioned by thought then that has to be brainwashing but if the experience is of such a nature that as it were it only reflects it only realises in a really true way the thought which happens only to be a reflection of the truth then the tables are turned then one realises actually it was a direction it was somebody pointing

461
01:00:29,000 --> 01:00:38,534
and not pushing what do you refer to as practice?

462
01:00:38,554 --> 01:00:41,699
what do you think a mark of a practice is?

463
01:00:42,701 --> 01:00:55,581
getting out of that well it's the methodology whereby you prove, this is in Buddhism

464
01:00:56,000 --> 01:01:22,597
it's the methodology whereby you prove that the concept or theory is right so the scientific method you know H2O and all that how do you prove that what's the methodology what's the practice the practice is the experiment so in a sense we are the experiment there is an enlightenment so who's going to experience that

465
01:01:22,983 --> 01:01:23,784
How are you going to get there?

466
01:01:23,824 --> 01:01:25,925
Do you know what I mean?

467
01:01:25,945 --> 01:01:26,827
That would be the practice.

468
01:01:30,831 --> 01:01:44,568
Well, that's all you can pass on because in a very post-modern sense, the Enlightenment is very personal, which is you.

469
01:01:46,190 --> 01:01:49,293
And if somebody says they're enlightened, you can't disprove it.

470
01:01:52,597 --> 01:01:54,601
I thought I might try and get more followers, you know.

471
01:01:56,643 --> 01:02:10,963
It's amazing what people can believe, you know.

472
01:02:11,023 --> 01:02:19,737
Yes.

473
01:02:20,121 --> 01:02:23,907
For myself, I don't know, I haven't reflected on that entirely.

474
01:02:23,927 --> 01:02:40,947
It's more in the sense of Buddhism is coming from an alien culture into this one and it's being picked up by certain historical waves coming through individuals.

475
01:02:41,536 --> 01:02:54,576
So, Buddhism as a guru-based thing through, say, the Tibetan traditions, it has a lot of, you know, Buddhism coming through as a very rational approach and investigative through Theravada.

476
01:02:56,097 --> 01:03:05,711
And it attracts, I mean, when I walk into a community of Tibetan Buddhists, it's a totally different feel to a Theravada community.

477
01:03:08,896 --> 01:03:10,159
There's a different feel about it.

478
01:03:13,177 --> 01:03:14,838
The people look different as well.

479
01:03:16,201 --> 01:03:16,541
It's funny.

480
01:03:17,523 --> 01:03:22,269
I can always know, I'm pretty sure that I can always know when somebody's in Zen.

481
01:03:23,211 --> 01:03:24,413
It's just the way they hold themselves.

482
01:03:25,936 --> 01:03:28,219
They've got this thing about them.

483
01:03:29,900 --> 01:03:30,902
I don't know, it's funny.

484
01:03:30,922 --> 01:03:31,143
Sorry?

485
01:03:31,603 --> 01:03:33,726
Do you know why we do something unbalanced?

486
01:03:33,746 --> 01:03:36,110
Like if I lived in Tibet, I'd have no choice.

487
01:03:36,150 --> 01:03:36,351
No.

488
01:03:36,610 --> 01:03:40,516
I'd have to go, we're in the West, holding to our personality types.

489
01:03:41,222 --> 01:03:42,826
Yeah.

490
01:03:43,086 --> 01:03:44,108
Yeah.

491
01:03:44,610 --> 01:03:45,311
Yeah.

492
01:03:45,911 --> 01:03:59,838
Yeah.

493
01:04:00,172 --> 01:04:05,201
in the East, in the Theravada tradition, you get a whole range of personality types.

494
01:04:05,221 --> 01:04:09,286
But when I see Western Theravada, it's a lot narrower.

495
01:04:09,306 --> 01:04:09,407
Yeah.

496
01:04:09,427 --> 01:04:10,728
No, I think that's true.

497
01:04:10,929 --> 01:04:11,570
I think that's true.

498
01:04:12,130 --> 01:04:14,795
We've become stereotypical in a particular vein.

499
01:04:15,175 --> 01:04:16,036
Yeah.

500
01:04:16,777 --> 01:04:24,550
I think Theravada Buddhism, because it's only that one Buddhism in a country, tends to have to open up to all these different personalities.

501
01:04:24,590 --> 01:04:29,117
So you've got people, you know, who...

502
01:04:30,532 --> 01:04:31,373
who just meditate.

503
01:04:31,393 --> 01:04:36,297
I mean, like the Mahasi, you know, he cuts through all that ritual stuff and everything, you wouldn't allow any of it.

504
01:04:36,998 --> 01:04:44,987
And yet on the other side, the devotional type, there are places they can go to to make these offerings and light candles and all that.

505
01:04:45,007 --> 01:04:45,407
Yes, you're right.

506
01:04:47,349 --> 01:04:57,219
But in another society like China, where different strains of Buddhism went, I don't know what it's like there in terms of the different forms.

507
01:04:57,239 --> 01:04:58,581
The same as Japan, of course.

508
01:04:58,914 --> 01:05:00,518
Soto, Rinzai, Shingon.

509
01:05:00,538 --> 01:05:08,092
Shingon is the Tantra.

510
01:05:08,172 --> 01:05:19,172
Maybe in a place like Japan, there are these different forms which attract a certain type, but they all live, as it were, within this idea of Buddhism.

511
01:05:19,735 --> 01:05:21,597
It's sort of an umbrella idea, I don't know.

512
01:05:25,780 --> 01:05:27,882
My experience is a bit different.

513
01:05:27,902 --> 01:05:36,132
I mean, although Theravada's sort of form, I've always said to myself, I've always been quite surprised at the different personalities.

514
01:05:37,873 --> 01:05:39,414
The teachings are different.

515
01:05:39,434 --> 01:05:44,141
Each personality teaches a different way, in a way.

516
01:05:44,340 --> 01:05:49,847
My experience is that there's quite a range of types of people in one tradition.

517
01:05:51,277 --> 01:05:59,945
Well, I think to a point, but if you look at Europe-wide, Theravadans attract Germans, Anglo-Saxons and Jews.

518
01:06:02,887 --> 01:06:06,530
It's very rare to find French, Spanish, Italians.

519
01:06:06,550 --> 01:06:08,452
Don't get them.

520
01:06:08,532 --> 01:06:12,315
I think I've known one Italian monk who didn't last.

521
01:06:16,599 --> 01:06:17,199
A couple of French.

522
01:06:17,721 --> 01:06:18,802
Where did they go?

523
01:06:18,822 --> 01:06:19,322
I don't know.

524
01:06:19,442 --> 01:06:20,543
I don't know what happened to him.

525
01:06:22,784 --> 01:06:25,989
He disappeared in a puff of spaghetti.

526
01:06:28,853 --> 01:06:31,476
Yeah, it's a sort of a mindset.

527
01:06:31,496 --> 01:06:34,081
It's very interesting.

528
01:06:34,101 --> 01:06:40,690
The French are huge into Tibetan Buddhism and the Spaniards and Italians too.

529
01:06:41,291 --> 01:06:42,632
It's really sort of...

530
01:06:42,652 --> 01:06:49,163
It's interesting, you know, because of that Catholicism, sort of perhaps open to it, whereas our more Protestant North...

531
01:06:54,356 --> 01:07:10,577
yeah well I didn't want to mean it was so blocked but

532
01:07:11,097 --> 01:07:12,701
I mean, I'll give you a lovely example.

533
01:07:12,721 --> 01:07:20,722
The vihara that I used to go to in Birmingham, just up the street, it was a Tibetan vihara.

534
01:07:21,262 --> 01:07:23,949
And I would occasionally go up there just to chat to the monk who was there.

535
01:07:23,969 --> 01:07:25,815
I was ordained then myself.

536
01:07:26,182 --> 01:07:55,228
and I turned to the kitchen he was a younger man than myself and he was talking about the Dalai Lama and his visit and he was talking to me he obviously knew I was Theravadana and he was talking to me and it was just straight you know he came and he gave this very good talk about this and then just at that moment a Tibetan nun came in English Tibetan nun

537
01:07:56,119 --> 01:08:02,347
And he got up to greet her and for a moment forgot I was there, as it were.

538
01:08:04,268 --> 01:08:05,650
And the Dalai Lama came and he passed me.

539
01:08:05,751 --> 01:08:08,054
I put up my hand and he touched my hand like that.

540
01:08:08,074 --> 01:08:08,653
And then he saw me.

541
01:08:13,340 --> 01:08:13,739
Classic.

542
01:08:18,865 --> 01:08:24,372
You said that whatever tradition, you need to be aware of these various, you know, the fatalities that go on.

543
01:08:25,685 --> 01:08:50,292
that's a good point yes I don't the way this is put in the commentaries is that you are that type I mean you can balance it a bit but in the sense you I suppose you do have to see yourself as clearly as you can and where your fault line is and then when you recognize that to work gently against it you know

544
01:08:55,452 --> 01:09:01,800
It was a bit, wasn't it?

545
01:09:02,020 --> 01:09:02,680
I agree with that.

546
01:09:03,242 --> 01:09:03,761
It was a bit.

547
01:09:03,782 --> 01:09:05,323
Well, this is Budagosa, you know.

548
01:09:06,405 --> 01:09:07,287
Some of you might know him.

549
01:09:08,608 --> 01:09:09,469
A great commentarian.

550
01:09:09,488 --> 01:09:10,970
Well, it was a bit negative.

551
01:09:10,990 --> 01:09:11,572
I have to agree.

552
01:09:11,612 --> 01:09:12,012
Where am I?

553
01:09:12,453 --> 01:09:23,686
In one of speculative temperament, there's frequent occurrence of such states as talkativeness, sociability, boredom with devotion to the profitable, failure to finish undertaking, smoking by night,

554
01:09:24,105 --> 01:09:27,050
Flaming by day and mental running hither and thither.

555
01:09:28,091 --> 01:09:31,076
Yeah, not much hope there, is there?

556
01:09:31,095 --> 01:09:33,340
The opposite is just this utter delusion.

557
01:09:33,739 --> 01:09:50,145
Yeah, I don't know.

558
01:09:50,164 --> 01:09:50,265
Yeah.

559
01:09:52,539 --> 01:10:01,912
So what happens then between a teacher and a student in the West?

560
01:10:01,931 --> 01:10:07,018
Well, I suppose it all depends... How does it differ?

561
01:10:07,037 --> 01:10:09,560
Oh, between a Westerner and a Western teacher?

562
01:10:10,301 --> 01:10:12,625
Oh, it varies, it varies.

563
01:10:14,122 --> 01:10:20,470
I mean, generally speaking, of course, just as this is only my personal experience, but I think it's true for everybody.

564
01:10:20,751 --> 01:10:34,429
I mean, if somebody, you know, is a law unto themselves, you know, they think, you know, they either don't come at all, or if they do come, it's to prove you're wrong.

565
01:10:37,131 --> 01:10:41,497
It's because they've had something niggling in their head and they want to come along and test it and say, well, you know.

566
01:10:45,240 --> 01:10:51,208
Most people, well, you've got various levels.

567
01:10:51,309 --> 01:10:56,135
I mean, the beginner will always be reliant on the teacher, much more so.

568
01:10:56,475 --> 01:11:02,023
But as a person becomes more confident and all that, of course, they don't come.

569
01:11:03,225 --> 01:11:04,565
And that's the whole idea, of course.

570
01:11:04,626 --> 01:11:07,930
The whole idea is to make a meditator autonomous, isn't it?

571
01:11:09,131 --> 01:11:11,555
So they have that inner confidence, they know what they're doing, you know?

572
01:11:11,956 --> 01:11:12,716
They don't have to come.

573
01:11:17,911 --> 01:11:23,220
I mean, it's a bad teacher who always makes the student feel that they're dependent on them.

574
01:11:24,421 --> 01:11:36,581
I think that's terrible.

575
01:11:36,600 --> 01:11:41,909
I mean, I always make the open desire at the end that they become enlightened in this very lifetime.

576
01:11:43,912 --> 01:11:45,015
But not before me.

577
01:11:49,618 --> 01:12:08,994
I consider that unjust.

578
01:12:13,395 --> 01:12:42,188
got more to run still and one of the things that I've got from post-modernism is not this sort of me generation thing that I agree with what you say about how that comes up so philosophically it can deconstruct all sorts of things including sort of core aspects of identity and it's the first time in the West that we've got anything that

579
01:12:42,859 --> 01:12:45,305
sort of chimes with an answer at all.

580
01:12:46,887 --> 01:12:48,810
And sometimes it's the opposite.

581
01:12:48,831 --> 01:12:59,771
It's actually a generation that sort of can deconstruct the self and can be in touch with experience.

582
01:13:02,131 --> 01:13:04,014
Yeah, no, thanks for pointing that out.

583
01:13:04,375 --> 01:13:10,425
Definitely one of the processes that the Buddha's constantly doing is deconstructing the human being.

584
01:13:10,444 --> 01:13:18,918
I mean, that's his main avenue of investigation, you know, where he splits you up into the five khandhas and the six sense spaces and all that sort of stuff.

585
01:13:18,939 --> 01:13:19,780
Yeah, absolutely.

586
01:13:22,444 --> 01:13:23,447
That process, definitely.

587
01:13:28,743 --> 01:13:34,451
It's a very radical thinking, and perhaps I was a bit too negative on it.

588
01:13:34,771 --> 01:13:47,730
It's a very radical thinking because I heard a program in which there were some very clear distinctions to prove that democracy was definitely not the best form of government, which we're completely sold on because of our modernism.

589
01:13:49,052 --> 01:13:53,619
You know, such examples, the fact that Hitler was voted in, you know, and Berlusconi.

590
01:13:57,987 --> 01:14:00,710
And Tony Blair, somebody would say.

591
01:14:01,832 --> 01:14:13,204
So it's like there's a trust in a sort of common reason and goodwill, but obviously there are situations when even that...

592
01:14:13,485 --> 01:14:14,567
I think it was Gandhi, wasn't it?

593
01:14:14,908 --> 01:14:16,488
Truth can be in a minority of one.

594
01:14:17,210 --> 01:14:18,612
I think he said that.

595
01:14:24,159 --> 01:14:48,226
And I think also the little bit that I understand about deconstruction and looking at the text and this idea that there are subtexts going on of which we are not aware, that whole, it's a sort of Freudianism really, isn't it, coming in, the whole idea that when you read a book or anything, a poem or anything, there's stuff going on underneath which you're not actually aware of.

596
01:14:49,489 --> 01:14:51,030
giving your interpretation.

597
01:14:51,070 --> 01:15:03,242
So, in terms of spiritual practice, the Buddha talks about these anusaya, these latent tendencies, which are sort of almost like these turbulences deep in the mind.

598
01:15:03,261 --> 01:15:06,005
We don't know they're there.

599
01:15:06,064 --> 01:15:11,930
It's like Jung might have called it the shadow, the part of us we're not aware.

600
01:15:11,949 --> 01:15:13,390
Often other people are, of course.

601
01:15:14,252 --> 01:15:18,636
And it's just coming through, puts nuances into our speech, gives it a twist.

602
01:15:20,675 --> 01:15:29,529
It gives us a shape of the body that we're not aware of, things like that.

603
01:15:31,131 --> 01:15:38,542
They talk about seeing things as they really are, often interlinked with the opening of the heart.

604
01:15:40,225 --> 01:15:48,757
And particularly in the Tibetan traditions, they talk about balancing wisdom and compassion, and in the Theravada traditions, metta and so forth.

605
01:15:51,015 --> 01:16:00,012
How is the heart addressed in Buddhism, which is not romanticized?

606
01:16:00,033 --> 01:16:03,078
In the West, we have this head-heart split.

607
01:16:03,539 --> 01:16:08,248
But there's very much, though, this knowing things as really are.

608
01:16:08,269 --> 01:16:11,756
It isn't a kind of transcendence of a mere intellectual experience.

609
01:16:11,775 --> 01:16:12,417
No, no.

610
01:16:13,695 --> 01:16:22,688
No, that phrase, seeing things as they really are, one understanding of that is to see these three characteristics.

611
01:16:22,728 --> 01:16:25,091
I mean, that's where the Buddha's always pointing his effort.

612
01:16:25,872 --> 01:16:41,813
This idea that everything's transient, there's nothing that can exist of itself, there's no such thing as an entity as such, and that if you have a wrong relationship with the sensual world, that some form of dissatisfaction arises.

613
01:16:41,792 --> 01:17:11,108
wrong relationship of identity and possession once the intelligence this intuitive intelligence has grasped that then the way it expresses itself through the phenomena of the body and personality changes so whereas before so we say one might have thought that it was good to help others

614
01:17:12,640 --> 01:17:18,126
But the subtext, as it were, in the postmodern sense is, I feel very happy when I do this.

615
01:17:19,167 --> 01:17:19,988
And you're not aware of it.

616
01:17:20,448 --> 01:17:23,931
So then you only help people because it makes you feel happy.

617
01:17:24,832 --> 01:17:27,256
And then you only do things for people that make you feel happy.

618
01:17:27,296 --> 01:17:28,917
So when somebody says, can you clean the toilet?

619
01:17:29,717 --> 01:17:30,378
You don't want to do it.

620
01:17:31,420 --> 01:17:32,942
It's not a real compassion.

621
01:17:32,962 --> 01:17:35,744
It's a compassion with this underlying label.

622
01:17:36,603 --> 01:18:04,359
when one sees the dependency upon compassion to make oneself happy and what that's actually doing in the sense of corrupting compassion and making the other one feel uncomfortable in some ways not good for me, not good for the other and all that when one sees that and it becomes open and there's a clarification of that thought a purification of the heart then you get that pure compassion coming through isn't that right?

623
01:18:04,698 --> 01:18:05,260
something like that?

624
01:18:08,193 --> 01:18:14,457
Yeah, and that's why he rates this as right understanding, right attitude, why it comes down the Eightfold Path.

625
01:18:17,301 --> 01:18:17,381
See?

626
01:18:17,400 --> 01:18:22,204
And then, right attitude, and then right speech, right action, right livelihood.

627
01:18:22,225 --> 01:18:24,846
See, it flows downward from right understanding.

628
01:18:30,771 --> 01:18:34,074
I mean, it's not as though you can split those two, split those three.

629
01:18:34,095 --> 01:18:37,778
I mean, obviously, if you're doing something, then it's right livelihood.

630
01:18:38,061 --> 01:19:05,739
you're saying something or it's right like that and by being aware one understands so the understanding comes out of the action as it were the right heart so it's those three things feed on each other really but the kernel of the practice is this awakening of that awareness that ability to catch these little thoughts that come up that tell us what we're really thinking you know

631
01:19:06,731 --> 01:19:09,095
which are often embarrassing or we don't want to see.

632
01:19:09,136 --> 01:19:13,585
Making that very plain to us.

633
01:19:13,604 --> 01:19:24,604
And then we see, ah, that's the underlying, that's the subtext, that's the bit of deconstruction I've got to do there.

634
01:19:24,625 --> 01:19:26,108
And that's when you bow to Derrida.

635
01:19:33,698 --> 01:19:36,261
Yeah, definitely.

636
01:19:36,421 --> 01:19:36,981
Yeah, yeah.

637
01:19:38,904 --> 01:19:41,568
I think Oxford refused to give him a PhD, didn't they?

638
01:19:41,587 --> 01:19:42,810
An honorary PhD, didn't they?

639
01:19:42,829 --> 01:19:43,430
Remember that?

640
01:19:43,451 --> 01:19:44,332
Cambridge, Cambridge!

641
01:19:44,351 --> 01:19:44,992
There we are.

642
01:19:45,092 --> 01:19:49,557
Dreadful, dreadful.

643
01:19:49,578 --> 01:19:51,720
Very recondite, that one.

644
01:19:51,740 --> 01:19:58,689
Are we somewhat caught up in Western thinking, Western dichotomising?

645
01:19:58,710 --> 01:20:00,212
Because I think these three...

646
01:20:15,886 --> 01:20:41,302
types of ethos that you've been talking about I suppose what you're saying in a way is that these should be all accepted they all have some value it's very difficult for us to listen to that without choosing one or the other rather than seeing that they're perhaps all part of the whole thing

647
01:20:44,118 --> 01:20:48,702
Well, I suppose if I were to... Well, I suppose it's an individual thing.

648
01:20:48,742 --> 01:20:50,724
It's balancing those three things within yourself.

649
01:20:51,003 --> 01:20:54,846
It's recognizing that there has been a revelation in terms of Buddhism.

650
01:20:55,547 --> 01:21:01,533
The Buddha discovered, didn't invent, remember, he discovered these particular things and he revealed them.

651
01:21:01,552 --> 01:21:04,414
So it is a revelation.

652
01:21:04,454 --> 01:21:11,942
Secondly, so that in a sense is an opening of our hearts to it, an opening of that possibility that revelation is actually true.

653
01:21:12,721 --> 01:21:13,703
That would be a...

654
01:21:15,167 --> 01:21:16,208
Pre-modern thing.

655
01:21:16,408 --> 01:21:17,390
Putting your trust in it.

656
01:21:18,131 --> 01:21:26,159
And that's what, remember, this word sadha means, as one of the five spiritual faculties, putting one's trust in, having a confidence in that.

657
01:21:26,180 --> 01:21:34,229
And then there's this business of really making it, just making it sure that it makes sense to you inwardly.

658
01:21:34,630 --> 01:21:36,051
So there's your rationality.

659
01:21:36,072 --> 01:21:39,876
It's not a case of just accepting it without question.

660
01:21:40,953 --> 01:21:48,426
And then finally, it has to become our personal take on reality through the practice.

661
01:21:48,447 --> 01:22:00,970
So, yeah, I would say it's this recognition, making sure that we're not unbalanced, that we're looking just simply to ourselves, that it has to be fully rational before we'll believe something.

662
01:22:01,185 --> 01:22:05,134
Not thinking that everything has to fit into some rational form.

663
01:22:05,354 --> 01:22:09,582
Because the Buddha warns us, he says, this stuff is beyond reason.

664
01:22:10,465 --> 01:22:12,108
It's subtle, it's beyond reason.

665
01:22:12,127 --> 01:22:13,631
You can't reason Nibbana.

666
01:22:14,512 --> 01:22:16,076
Because it's beyond words.

667
01:22:16,095 --> 01:22:19,363
He says, words only go so far, then they stop.

668
01:22:21,773 --> 01:22:28,762
On the other hand, he's constantly urging us to investigate and to argue with him in a sort of dialogue.

669
01:22:29,024 --> 01:22:32,548
And some of the scriptures, remember, people come to him and they don't agree.

670
01:22:32,588 --> 01:22:35,393
They go away tutting, as it says, clicking their tongues.

671
01:22:36,094 --> 01:22:40,439
Rubbish.

672
01:22:40,460 --> 01:22:41,622
He's not unhappy thereby.

673
01:22:41,662 --> 01:22:43,524
That's what he says.

674
01:22:44,506 --> 01:22:49,012
But when somebody actually receives the Dharma and becomes a follower, he's full of joy.

